Annotation.note:
A problem posed at International Mathematical Olympiad:
$M$ is any point on the side $AB$ of the triangle $ABC$. $r$, $r_1$, $r_2$ are the radii of the circles inscribed in $ABC$, $AMC$, $BMC$. $q$ is the radius of the circle on the opposite side of $AB$ to $C$, touching the three sides of $AB$ and the extensions of $CA$ and $CB$. Similarly, $q_1$ and $q_2$. Prove that $r_1 r_2 q = r q_1 q_2$.
\begin{keywords} geometry theorem proving \end{keywords}
